**Pros: **The ViewModel is much more simple with no side effects.&nbsp; 
**Cons:** The XAML is ugly as sin.&nbsp; It also changes the behavior of the ListBox in a subtle way.&nbsp; Every time you select an item, the command fires, not just when it changes.&nbsp; This is my LEAST favorite approach.&nbsp; We can do better

### Method 3: Bind Commands to the ListBox

The final mechanism is my favorite.&nbsp; Even though [Prism](http://compositewpf.codeplex.com/) doesnt give us the ability to bind commands to ListBoxes, we can extend their attached behavior infrastructure such that all ListBoxes and ComboBoxes (or anything that derives from Selector) can take advantage of it.&nbsp; The ViewModel doesnt change from Method 2, but the XAML does:

